[
    {
        "content": "<p>In constructive mathematics one sometimes needs to consider the relation on two sets <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">B</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span></span></span></span> given by \"we have a function <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo>:</mo><mi>A</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">f : A \\to B</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span></span></span></span>, and a function <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>g</mi><mo>:</mo><mi>B</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">g : B \\to A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">g</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span>\". It is in general stronger than saying that the propositional truncations of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">B</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span></span></span></span> are equivalent.</p>\n<p>The HoTT book introduces (but never really uses in an essential way) this notion under the name \"logical equivalence\". I'm not that much of a fan because I understand logic as being about propositions, and it could be okay to say that our \"propositions\" could have multiple inhabitants, except that in the context of HoTT the term \"proposition\" is well-established to mean something else, and so it seems more reasonable to say that a \"logical equivalence\" is something that becomes an equivalence after propositional truncation.</p>\n<p>Does anyone have another name they prefer? e.g., I suppose this notion must come up when working with E-categories, so maybe \"E-equivalence\" (ugh)?</p>",
        "id": 347096861,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1680691452
    },
    {
        "content": "<blockquote>\n<p>and so it seems more reasonable to say that a \"logical equivalence\" is something that becomes an equivalence after propositional truncation.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>You might call it a (-1)-equivalence then?</p>",
        "id": 347098345,
        "sender_full_name": "Tom de Jong",
        "timestamp": 1680691784
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(More specifically, the HoTT book introduces the term \"logical equivalence\" for arbitrary types, but then only ever applies it to propositions.)</p>",
        "id": 347098542,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1680691820
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"355959\">Tom de Jong</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/266967-general.3A-mathematics/topic/logical.20equivalence/near/347098345\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<blockquote>\n<p>and so it seems more reasonable to say that a \"logical equivalence\" is something that becomes an equivalence after propositional truncation.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>You might call it a (-1)-equivalence then?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I'm happy to call those (-1)-equivalences, but I'm looking for a name for the other notion--where there is no truncation involved, just maps that don't have to be inverse to each other.</p>",
        "id": 347098683,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1680691847
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Oh, I misunderstood, sorry.</p>",
        "id": 347099130,
        "sender_full_name": "Tom de Jong",
        "timestamp": 1680691934
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I see how my question was unclear, but I'll just take it as more evidence that the phrase \"logical equivalence\" is confusing. <span aria-label=\"upside down\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f643\" role=\"img\" title=\"upside down\">:upside_down:</span></p>",
        "id": 347099349,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1680691990
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I've always used the terminology \"logically equivalent\" several times, although to be fair it has caused confusion sometimes. I've seen these described as \"biimplications\" which is maybe more descriptive.</p>",
        "id": 347099824,
        "sender_full_name": "Andrew Swan",
        "timestamp": 1680692117
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>But you want a name for having maps in both directions, right? But if you do have such maps, then they are (-1)-equivalences, as their (-1)-truncations become equivalences. What is this \"other notion\" you're referring to?</p>",
        "id": 347100073,
        "sender_full_name": "Tom de Jong",
        "timestamp": 1680692176
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>A (-1)-equivalence might not be a, well, logical equivalence. For example there might not be any map <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∣</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∣</mi><mi>A</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∣</mi><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∣</mi><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><mo>→</mo><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">||A||_{-1} \\to A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">∣∣</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mord\">∣</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\">∣</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3011em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">−</span><span class=\"mord mtight\">1</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.2083em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span>.</p>",
        "id": 347100393,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1680692259
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Ah, of course, thank you</p>",
        "id": 347104665,
        "sender_full_name": "Tom de Jong",
        "timestamp": 1680693205
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"276787\">Andrew Swan</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/266967-general.3A-mathematics/topic/logical.20equivalence/near/347099824\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I've always used the terminology \"logically equivalent\" several times, although to be fair it has caused confusion sometimes. I've seen these described as \"biimplications\" which is maybe more descriptive.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I've also seen \"biimplication\", which seems reasonable. But what would you say for the relation of standing in biimplication? Maybe you'd just say A and B stand in biimplication?</p>",
        "id": 347140949,
        "sender_full_name": "Sam Speight",
        "timestamp": 1680700627
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"276480\">Reid Barton</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/266967-general.3A-mathematics/topic/logical.20equivalence/near/347096861\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>The HoTT book introduces (but never really uses in an essential way) this notion under the name \"logical equivalence\". I'm not that much of a fan because I understand logic as being about propositions, and it could be okay to say that our \"propositions\" could have multiple inhabitants, except that in the context of HoTT the term \"proposition\" is well-established to mean something else</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>In fairness, I would like to point out that that \"well-established\" usage did not become established until somewhat after the HoTT Book was written.  The book uses \"mere proposition\" for a <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">(-1)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord\">−</span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>-truncated type.</p>\n<p>Personally, while I'm okay with dropping the \"mere\", I do think it's overly limiting to say that \"logic\" is only about <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">(-1)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord\">−</span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>-truncated types, so I don't see anything wrong with \"logical equivalence\".</p>",
        "id": 347217202,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1680716469
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>this happens a lot in database theory where they call it \"homomorphic equivalence\"</p>",
        "id": 347220103,
        "sender_full_name": "Ryan Wisnesky",
        "timestamp": 1680717287
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>That's a good point about \"mere proposition\"--I think I remembered <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mtext mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">isProp</mtext></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\textsf{isProp}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord textsf\">isProp</span></span></span></span></span>, and forgot about the \"mere\".</p>",
        "id": 347222906,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1680718110
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I'm not saying logic always has to be about (-1)-truncated types, just about whatever \"propositions\" means in context. For example if your mathematical framework doesn't let you form (-1)-truncations, then it would definitely be a bad idea to interpret \"proposition\" as (-1)-type.</p>",
        "id": 347223263,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1680718213
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I'm okay with \"proposition\" meaning (-1)-type but \"logic\" being interpreted more expansively.</p>",
        "id": 347223949,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1680718414
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>What makes some mathematics not logic?</p>",
        "id": 347224148,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1680718468
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Logic is the superstructure in which mathematics is written.  The mathematics itself is not the same as the logic.</p>",
        "id": 347224241,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1680718499
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So for example type theory is also a kind of logic, or part of logic.</p>",
        "id": 347226387,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1680719113
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>That seems like a reasonable usage, but then I don't see any connection to the meaning of \"logical equivalence\".</p>",
        "id": 347226507,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1680719152
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I guess the argument is that \"logic\" is a point of view on type theory that emphasizes the inhabitation of types rather than the identity of their elements.</p>",
        "id": 347226753,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1680719234
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Here's a not-sure-if-serious suggestion:<br>\nequivalence relation : pseudo-equivalence relation :: logical equivalence (= (-1)-equivalence) : logical pseudo-equivalence?</p>",
        "id": 347246596,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1680725976
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I don't think it would be a good idea to use \"logical equivalence\" to mean (-1)-equivalence.  If you don't want to use it at all, that's one thing, but using it with a similar but different definition seems to me like a recipe for confusion.</p>",
        "id": 347247807,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1680726486
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I am also tempted to coin \"pseudoproposition\" for a set/type which we would like to treat as though it were (-1)-truncated. Basically a setoid in which every two elements are related in a unique way.</p>",
        "id": 347248783,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1680726868
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>What about \"propositionoid\"?  (-:O</p>",
        "id": 347249070,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1680726966
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>That would make sense too but maybe it doesn't score so highly on the \"is it really a word\" test.</p>",
        "id": 347250640,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1680727588
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yeah.</p>",
        "id": 347251598,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1680727988
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I could probably live with \"pseudoproposition\".</p>",
        "id": 347251631,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1680728001
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It does have an <a href=\"https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/pseudoproposition\">unfortunate meaning</a> in ordinary English, however.</p>",
        "id": 347251721,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1680728032
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>And pseudo- is sort of overloaded as it is.</p>",
        "id": 347251995,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1680728141
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>But the idea is that a pseudoequivalence relation is like an equivalence relation, except valued in pseudopropositions rather than propositions.</p>",
        "id": 347252103,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1680728178
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yes.  But, as you say, \"pseudo\" also has the meaning in category theory of \"up to isomorphism\", so maybe \"pseudo-equivalence relation\" is not the best terminology to be generalizing from.</p>",
        "id": 347252678,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1680728400
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>In the terminology of my paper <a href=\"http://cahierstgdc.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/SHULMAN-LXIV-1.pdf\">The derivator of setoids</a> (which comes from the theory of derivators), a logical equivalence can be called a \"<span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></mrow></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\rm Set_{pos}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.9694em;vertical-align:-0.2861em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Se</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">t</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.1514em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathrm mtight\">pos</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.2861em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>-equivalence\", the idea being that it becomes an equivalence in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></mrow></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\rm Set_{pos}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.9694em;vertical-align:-0.2861em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Se</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">t</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.1514em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathrm mtight\">pos</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.2861em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>, the poset reflection of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\rm Set</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Set</span></span></span></span></span>.</p>",
        "id": 347253230,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1680728611
    }
]